@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_pubscr "YP/Option -pubscr"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-pubscr (-ps) <name>@{ub}

À<name> (case-sensitive!) is the name of the public screen

Àif the specified screen can't be found then the default public screen
 will be used instead

Àthe window will open in the top left corner of that screen

Àthis display mode is quite slow on @{"AGA" link usage_disp_aga} screens but plays smoothly
 on @{"CyberGfx" link usage_disp_cybergfx} screens
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_modeid "YP/Option -modeID"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-modeID (-mid) <hex number or 'req'>@{ub}


Àopen a custom screen for playback
 (see also: Display types @{"AGA" link usage_disp_aga} and @{"CyberGfx" link usage_disp_cybergfx})

Àthe modeID is a hexadecimal number, don't use any prefixes (like $ or 0x)

Àif 'req' (without the quotes) or an unavailable modeID is specified an ASL
 screenmode requester opens

Àto get the modeID of a certain screen mode use 'req' and the
 option @{"-verbose" link opt_verbose}

Àexamples: LoRes                      0
           HiRes-Laced             8004
           Multiscan Productivity 39024
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_info "YP/Option -info"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-info (-i)@{ub}


Àprint some information about the anim(s) (like @{"-verbose" link opt_verbose}) but don't play
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_wait "YP/Option -wait"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-wait (-w)@{ub}


Àopen a black screen before the first and after the last anim,
 continue with <Space>

Àuseful for video recording because you know exactly when the anim starts

Àworks on @{"AGA" link usage_disp_aga} hardware and custom screens only

Àsee also option @{"-waitd" link opt_waitd}
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_waitd "YP/Option -waitd"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-waitd (-wd)@{ub}


ÀYP waits for the break signal Ctrl-D after having opened and pre-loaded
 the animation(s), just before the display opens

Àespecially useful for starting the playback of an anim sequence
 (using the @{"-batch" link usage_batch}-mode) exactly "on cue"

Àsending Ctrl-C instead of Ctrl-D quits YP, in case you decided
 not to watch the show this time :-)

Àsee also option @{"-wait" link opt_wait}
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_verbose "YP/Option -verbose"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-verbose (-v)@{ub}


Àprint some information about the anim(s) and also some more warnings
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_stats "YP/Option -stats"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-stats (-st)@{ub}


Àprint statistics (played frames, play time, frames-per-second) on exit
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_nodeactivate "YP/Option -nodeactivate"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-nodeactivate (-nd)@{ub}


Àdo not pause and restore system colors when window gets deactivated

Àpublic screen window only (option @{"-pubscr" link opt_pubscr})
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_fastblit "YP/Option -fastblit"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-fastblit (-fb)@{ub}


Àuse faster blitting routine for copying image data into the window,
 this usually leads to even more 'flickering'

À@{"AGA" link usage_disp_aga} public screen window only (option @{"-pubscr" link opt_pubscr})
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_scale "YP/Option -scale"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-scale (-sc)@{ub}


Àmake the window resizeable, the anims are scaled to the current window size
 which is quite slow (thats why it's optional)

Àcurrently for @{"AGA" link usage_disp_aga} public screen window only (option @{"-pubscr" link opt_pubscr})
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_noborders "YP/Option -noborders"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-noborders (-nb)@{ub}


Àthe window will open without borders, dragbar, gadgets
 (useful for playing inside a background picture)

Àpublic screen window only (option @{"-pubscr" link opt_pubscr})
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_windowleft "YP/Option -windowleft"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-windowleft (-wl) <number>@{ub}


Àspecify the window's horizontal position (default: 0)

Àpublic screen window only (option @{"-pubscr" link opt_pubscr})
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_windowtop "YP/Option -windowtop"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-windowtop (-wt) <number>@{ub}


Àspecify the window's vertical position (default: 0)

Àpublic screen window only (option @{"-pubscr" link opt_pubscr})
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_noinput "YP/Option -noinput"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-noinput (-ni)@{ub}


Àall inputs in the player window (keystrokes, window (de-)activation)
 are ignored. the palette of the public screen is not changed.

Àthe only ways to end YP are to send Ctrl-C or to limit the number
 of frames shown using @{"-lastframe" link opt_lastframe}

Àpublic screen window only (option @{"-pubscr" link opt_pubscr})
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_fastxpk "YP/Option -fastXPK"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-fastXPK (-fx)@{ub}


Àuse YP's internal unpacking routines (currently for FAST, NUKE, RAKE, MASH)
 instead of xpkmaster.library and the corresponding compressor libraries

Àa significant speed increase can be achieved by this because using
 xpkmaster.library results in some overhead:
  -open/close the compressor library for each XpkUnpack() (=every frame!)
  -checksum the packed data before unpacking it
 the latter function can of course be considered as useful because it
 avoids crashing the unpacking routine on corrupted data, but if you are
 sure that a YAFA anim is not corrupted (after playing it without '-fx')
 the risk of crashing YP's unpacking routines should be nearly 0 (ZERO :-)

Àthe unpacking routines used in YP are based on these compressors:
  -xpkFAST.library V1.06 (27-Jul-94) by Christian von Roques
  -xpkNUKE.library V1.1  (02-Nov-92) by Urban Dominik M³ller
  -xpkRAKE.library V1.7  (06-Sep-95) by Karsten Dagef÷rde
  -xpkMASH.library V1.98 (30-Mar-95) by Zdenek Kabelac
 they were testet with many different files and seem to work well.
 if you encounter problems with them (an anim plays without '-fx' but
 crashes with it) then please contact @{"me" link contact} and also specify which versions
 of xpkmaster.library and the compressor were used for packing.
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_firstframe "YP/Option -firstframe"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-firstframe (-ff) <number>@{ub}


Àthe first frame of the anim to be played,
 frames before this are skipped
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_lastframe "YP/Option -lastframe"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-lastframe (-lf) <number>@{ub}


Àthe last frame of the anim to be played

Àcan be greater than the number of frames in the anim,
 playing will restart if necessary    
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_speed "YP/Option -speed"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-speed (-s) <number>@{ub}


Àset the playing speed for the anim,
 overrides the value contained in the file

Àthe speed value is the number of video frames that each anim frame
 is shown, the smaller the value the faster it plays, minimum is 1
 (see also @{"-fps" link opt_fps})
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_fps "YP/Option -framespersecond"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-framespersecond (-fps) <number>@{ub}


Àset the playing speed for the anim,
 overrides the speed value contained in the file

Àthe explanation below is for @{"AGA" link usage_disp_aga} OS screens only,
 for @{"CyberGfx" link usage_disp_cybergfx} screens YP uses the CIA timer at a 50Hz frequency (PAL-like)

Àdue to the strict synchronization of the player with the
 video frames (double buffering is done by a VBlank IRQ)
 it is only possible to play at certain discrete FPS values
 depending on the frame rate of the monitor driver.
 here some examples: (FPS = VIDEO_HZ / SPEED)

                   speed|  1  |  2  |  3  |  4  |  5  |  6  |  7  |  8
                   -----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+------
 50Hz (eg. PAL)     FPS | 50  | 25  | 16.6| 12.5| 10  |  8.3|  7.1|  6.2
                   -----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+------
 60Hz (eg. NTSC)    FPS | 60  | 30  | 20  | 15  | 12  | 10  |  8.5|  7.5
                   -----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+------
 72Hz (eg. EURO72)  FPS | 72  | 36  | 24  | 18  | 14.4| 12  | 10.2|  9

Àthe specified FPS value will be adjusted to the nearest
 discrete value if necessary (see @{"-verbose" link opt_verbose} output)
   specifying "-fps 15" for example yields
   PAL: 16.6 fps    NTSC: 15 fps    EURO72: 14.4 fps
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_buffers "YP/Option -buffers"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-buffers (-b) <number>@{ub}


Àset the number of frame buffers for the anim, default is 6

Àthe buffers are needed for smooth playing while loading from disk,
 the best number depends on several things (average loading speed,
 file system fragmentation, CPU and DMA speed etc.)
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_asyncbuff "YP/Option -asyncbuff"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-asyncbuff (-ab) <number>@{ub}


Àset the size of each of the two asynchronous load buffers for the anim,
 the number is in KBytes, default is 64

Àlarge buffers can make loading faster (depends on drive, filesystem etc.),
 small buffers reduce memory usage but usually decrease loading performance
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_caching "YP/Option -caching"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-caching (-c)@{ub}


Àmake YP load the complete anim to memory before starting to play
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_loadall "YP/Option -loadall"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-loadall (-l)@{ub}


Àmake YP load and XPK-decompress the complete anim before starting to play
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_zoom "YP/Option -zoom"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-zoom (-z)@{ub}


Àperform realtime 2x2 zooming while playing

À@{"AGA" link usage_disp_aga} hardware screen only
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_dither "YP/Option -dither"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-dither (-d)@{ub}


Àperform realtime 2x2 zooming with simple dithering while playing

À@{"AGA" link usage_disp_aga} hardware screen only
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_gray "YP/Option -gray"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-gray (-g)@{ub}


Àrender a "deep" anim (15 or 24 bits) to 8 bits gray
 (see also @{"tech stuff" link tech_3})

Àonly on 8bit @{"displays" link usage_disp}
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_drgb "YP/Option -discretergb"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-discretergb (-drgb)@{ub}


Àrender a "deep" anim (15 or 24 bits) to 8 bits "Discrete RGB"
 (see also @{"tech stuff" link tech_3})

Àonly on 8bit @{"displays" link usage_disp}
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_drgb2 "YP/Option -discretergb2"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-discretergb2 (-drgb2)@{ub}


Àrender a "deep" anim (15 or 24 bits) to 8 bits "Discrete RGB 2"
 (see also @{"tech stuff" link tech_3})

Àthe anim appears four times as large on screen (double width and height)
 which is definitely not the same effect like @{"-zoom" link opt_zoom}.

Àonly on 8bit @{"displays" link usage_disp}
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_ham8 "YP/Option -ham8"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-ham8 (-h8)@{ub}


Àrender a "deep" anim (15 or 24 bits) to 8 bits "HAM8"
 (see also @{"tech stuff" link tech_3})

Àthe anim appears four times wider on screen.
 to make it look like "Low Res" you have to use "Super-High Res".
 in the case no @{"-modeID" link opt_modeid} was specified YP does this on itself.

ÀNOTE: only these AGA monitor drivers support suitable resolutions:
   -EURO36:  Super-High Res (1280x200)    -modeID 79020
   -NTSC:    Super-High Res (1280x200)    -modeID 19020
   -PAL:     Super-High Res (1280x256)    -modeID 29020
   -SUPER72: 800 x 150                    -modeID 89028
 of course your choice is not restricted to these modes, but all other ones
 will give you a strange kind of "wide-screen" show.
 also note that there are no "double scan" modes (DBLPAL, MULTISCAN etc.)
 in the list above - bad luck for all you people with non-15kHz monitors.
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_ham6 "YP/Option -ham6"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-ham6 (-h6)@{ub}


Àrender a "deep" anim (15 or 24 bits) to 6 bits "HAM6"
 (see also @{"tech stuff" link tech_3})

Àthe anim appears four times wider on screen.
 to make it look like "Low Res" you have to use "Super-High Res".
 in the case no @{"-modeID" link opt_modeid} was specified YP does this on itself.

ÀNOTE: only these AGA monitor drivers support suitable resolutions:
   -EURO36:  Super-High Res (1280x200)    -modeID 79020
   -NTSC:    Super-High Res (1280x200)    -modeID 19020
   -PAL:     Super-High Res (1280x256)    -modeID 29020
   -SUPER72: 800 x 150                    -modeID 89028
 of course your choice is not restricted to these modes, but all other ones
 will give you a strange kind of "wide-screen" show.
 also note that there are no "double scan" modes (DBLPAL, MULTISCAN etc.)
 in the list above - bad luck for all you people with non-15kHz monitors.
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_module "YP/Option -module"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-module (-mod) <file name> <start> <stop>@{ub}


Àthe specified ProTracker module is loaded to Chip-RAM before anim playing
 starts

Àmodule playing starts/stops when the specified anim frames are reached
 (NOTE for @{"batch files" link batchexample})

Àmodules are always loaded using XPK (so YP recognizes uncompressed and
 XPK- or PowerPacker-compressed files)
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_sample "YP/Option -sample"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-sample (-smp) <file name> <start> <stop> <channel> <volume> <repeat>@{ub}


Àthe specified IFF-8SVX sample is loaded to ChipRAM before anim playing
 starts

Àsample playing starts/stops when the specified anim frames are reached
 (NOTE for @{"batch files" link batchexample})

Àchannel is a number 0...3, volume is a number 0...64,
 repeat is a number: 0=loop forever, other=number of loops

Àstereo samples are supported, channel has no meaning then because YP takes
 two channels for stereo playing automatically

Àsamples larger than 128 KBytes are not played correctly, this is due to
 some limitations in the AMIGA audio hardware
@ENDNODE
@NODE opt_executable "YP/Option -executable"
@TOC usage_shell

@{b}-executable (-exe) <command> <start>@{ub}


Àthe specified AmigaDOS command is executed when the anim frame <start>
 is reached (NOTE for @{"batch files" link batchexample})

ÀNOTE:
  use this with care when YP runs on @{"AGA" link usage_disp_aga} hardware or OS screen!
  the command may not do any output to a shell window,
  it may not do anything with windows and screens.
  (actually the complete Intuition system may not be used!
  see also @{"tech stuff" link tech_2})

Àif <start> is 0 (zero) the command is executed _before_ the player's display
 is opened (it is allowed to use Intuition)
@ENDNODE
@NODE batchexample "YP/Batch file example"
@TOC usage_batch

   This is an example of a batch file used by YP:

---cut here-------
;
; comment lines have a ';' as first character

; empty lines are allowed too
; every (real) line contains one animation (and maybe anim options)
; sound options can be appended to every animation line
;       NOTE: in batch files the start/stop frames for sounds
;             are frame numbers in the whole anim sequence
;             rather than frame numbers of individual anims
ram:example1.yafa -c -lf 200  -mod ram:mod1 1 500
ram:example2.yafa -z -ff 20 -lf 400
---cut here-------
@ENDNODE
@NODE help_me "Infect! There is no medicine against."
@TOC help_me
@PREV help_me
@NEXT help_me

 You're looking for help?

 Haha, LAMER!
@ENDNODE

